{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01RD6B9CbmzPNSJLp2MemQg5","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The issue is that `_ai_pending_tasks`, `_ai_message_buffers`, and `_ai_debounce_config` can accumulate stale entries. Looking at the code:\n\n- `_ai_pending_tasks` entries are removed in `_run_ai_response` via `.pop(contact_key, None)` on line 38, but if the task raises an unexpected exception before that line, the entry stays\n- `_ai_message_buffers` entries are removed via `.pop(contact_key, [])` on line 37\n- `_ai_debounce_config` entries are removed via `.pop(contact_key, ...)` on line 34\n\n\n- The cleanup happens in the try block, so if an exception occurs before those pops, entries leak. When a task is cancelled, the buffer and config entries aren't cleaned up either, though the buffer is intentionally preserved since a new task will replace the cancelled one when a fresh message arrives.\n- The real problem is when a task completes with an exception — `_ai_pending_tasks` still holds a reference to the done task, and `_ai_message_buffers` or `_ai_debounce_config` might have leftover data if the error happened before cleanup.\n\nThe solution is to add a `finally` block in `_run_ai_response` that always cleans up stale entries from `_ai_pending_tasks` for completed tasks, while being careful not to discard buffers on cancellation since the next task needs them. I should also ensure buffers are cleaned on error paths.\n\nLooking at the actual execution order: `debounce_config` gets popped first, then the sleep happens, then `message_buffers` and `pending_tasks` are popped. If an exception occurs during the sleep, only `debounce_config` is cleaned up. If it happens after the sleep but before the other pops, we get partial cleanup. The key insight is that `debounce_config` is always removed first, so the real leak is in the other two dictionaries when exceptions occur mid-cleanup.\n\nThe most realistic leak scenario is when tasks get cancelled — they leave stale entries in `_ai_pending_tasks` that never get removed.\n\nActually, looking at the flow more carefully: when a new message arrives, the old task gets cancelled and a new one overwrites the entry, so the reference is gone. When the new task completes, it cleans itself up. So that's actually handled. The real vulnerability is edge cases that might slip through over long uptime, so adding a periodic cleanup sweep would be a good safety net.\n\nNow I'll add a periodic cleanup function and wrap the critical sections in a `finally` block for extra protection.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6475,"cache_read_input_tokens":47106,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":6475},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c65344f3-6aa1-4b02-b3ae-01430f0d6aae","uuid":"919bf4a8-3644-4ad2-9ff1-2f3483eebb31"}
